commit.message: g_mime_object_get_header can return null in the gir

Updated README.md

Removed reference about mailing lists and replaced with the discussion
forum link.
bumped version to 3.2.14
fixed compile warning

Revert base64 decoder optimizations to support chunked base64

Fixes issue #150

Improved URL scanner to properly handle domains that start with digits

Fixes issue #152
Some urls add params without a /

build: avoid useless configure-time checks

Checking for the sizeof various types and defining preprocessor macros
for them, is pointless, since the *only* effect these had was defining
said macros... and the code never did anything with them.

This speeds up running configure and is less confusing to readers. It's
also less confusing to porters, as evidenced by the VS projects which
contain out of date copies of the config.h files that are missing some
of these unused checks.

Make gir follow the spec.

Without this change, the generated gir doesn't follow the spec and some
tools fail to parse the gir. This isn't a problem overall because these
are skipped because they are marked as not introspectable. But for some
languages (rust), the introspectable tag is more of a suggestion and
(skip)-ed objects and functions are still parsed. Not having a name for
the type creates an error which in part breaks the gir generation tool.
Add some nullable annotations

Fixes a memory bug with parser option

In the last PR for parser options, there is a free after use.

Adding a GNotifyDestroy to parser options callback.

This makes g_mime_parser_options_set_warning_callback introspectable.
For C code currently using this function, adding NULL as the last
parameter will enable same semantics as the old code.

Fix some warnings from g_string_free.

Using the latest version of glib, glib has started to report a warning
if the return value of g_string_free isn't used, when free_segment is set
FALSE. It also makes the code tidier.
Fix buffer overrun

Add some annotations to supress warnings

These annotations are not strictly needed but removes warnings

improve quoting

Prior to this change, when formatting address lists without RFC-2047 encoding,
the display names are quoted if and only if they contain specials that are preceded by
an even number of dquotes without checking wheter the "qstrings" are terminated.
This means that the two address lists

    =?UTF-8?Q?=22=20=3Cfoo=40bar=2Ecom=3E=2C=20=22?= <test@mail.net>
    =?UTF-8?Q?=22=?= <foo@bar.com>, =?UTF-8?Q?=22?= <test@mail.net>

were identically formatted as »" <foo@bar.com>, " <test@mail.net>«.

With this change, display names are also quoted when they end in an unterminated
quoted string. The second address list is now formatted as
»"\"" <foo@bar.com>, "\"" <test@mail.net>«.
Make GMimeEncryptFlags a bitfield in the gir
Correct some annotations for gir

Properly handle GDateTime UTC offsets with non-zero seconds

Fixes issue #134

Fixed rfc2047 token decoding logic for base64 encodings

A previous optimization added a new 'eof' state which prevents the
base64 decoder from decoding any further data. Since state is carried
over between rfc2047 tokens, we need to reset this state if it ever
gets set.

Fixes issue #133
test-mime: Print more details on header decoding failure

Use gtk-doc ulink syntax in doc comments instead of <a href=...>

Fixes issue #131

Add the internet_address_list_append_parse() prototype definition to internet-address.h

Fixes issue #128

Avoid clearing a header list if it is being appended to.

I think this resolves a copy/paste error that was introduced in
4a80ae527df9aa36fe50fac0878207a31d4d6b72.

The logic for `message_add_addresses` is that it is supposed to just
be appending to a list of addresses, rather than trying to re-merge a
series of addresses.

It looks like the function's framing was copy/pasted from
`message_update_addresses`, which does the more complete
re-build/re-merge.

However, `message_update_addresses` starts with an initial
`internet_address_list_clear`, and then proceeds to cycle through the
entire list of headers, trying to collect the ones that match the
field name, so clearing the address list initially makes sense.

For `message_add_addresses` though, the goal is just to append to the
current list that already exists, so the list should not be initially
cleared.

Fixes: #129
bumped version to 3.2.13

Optimize parsing of messages with lots of address headers

Fixes issue #126

Use a new _intenet_address_list_append_parse() to reduce memory allocations

If a message has a ton of To: headers, for example, we were allocating a new
InternetAddressList for each To: header and concatenating them onto a single
list after parsing them.

This improves performance by ~20% for those types of cases.
